Numbers in each bucket are logged

115
00:08:11,969 --> 00:08:16,699
and the data analyzed
so as to obtain figures on population density,

116
00:08:16,699 --> 00:08:20,680
average size
and population structure.

117
00:08:20,680 --> 00:08:25,110
For this second focus,
I would like to introduce you to an initiative

118
00:08:25,110 --> 00:08:29,219
from
l'Agence Française des Aires Marines Protégées,

119
00:08:29,219 --> 00:08:32,930
which has been producing monitoring charts
for some years now.

120
00:08:32,930 --> 00:08:37,409
Let me remind you again that the principles
used for this monitoring

121
00:08:37,409 --> 00:08:40,980
are the same as those given at the beginning
of this session:

122
00:08:40,980 --> 00:08:44,370
thoroughness, method and consistency.

123
00:08:44,370 --> 00:08:55,440
Here we have a rather interesting example
of

124
00:08:55,440 --> 00:09:01,250
a restitution.

125
00:09:01,250 --> 00:09:05,500
This tool has been developed thanks to a partnership
between the managers,

126
00:09:05,500 --> 00:09:09,560
scientific associates, communities and in
partnership with

127
00:09:09,560 --> 00:09:12,750
several marine protected areas.

128
00:09:12,750 --> 00:09:16,570
Note that this tool is very useful
in a communication process.

129
00:09:16,570 --> 00:09:18,700
It's very visual.

130
00:09:18,700 --> 00:09:21,040
All of the data is gathered.

131
00:09:21,040 --> 00:09:25,760
Therefore we have a dashboard with the evolution
of all the factors.

132
00:09:25,760 --> 00:09:29,120
The graphical aspect makes it easy to follow.

133
00:09:29,120 --> 00:09:34,060
This allows for an easier way to communicate
with all audiences.

134
00:09:34,060 --> 00:09:39,730
What is also interesting in this example
is that the monitoring has been done on 2

135
00:09:39,730 --> 00:09:43,970
levels:
on both the scale of a single protected area,

136
00:09:43,970 --> 00:09:50,260
and of a network of protected areas,
to provide some degree of consistency.

137
00:09:50,260 --> 00:09:55,140
In summary, I would like to insist on some
aspects of this monitoring.

138
00:09:55,140 --> 00:09:59,440
First there is a strong concern in measuring
the management impacts.

139
00:09:59,440 --> 00:10:03,930
For that reason, what we just saw, biological
monitorings,

140
00:10:03,930 --> 00:10:09,100
and socioeconomic monitoring are very important,
even if they are not often used and if they

141
00:10:09,100 --> 00:10:11,060
need a lot of resources.

142
00:10:11,060 --> 00:10:15,440
Please also note that several levels of monitoring
are generally put in place

143
00:10:15,440 --> 00:10:20,330
in protected areas: the monitoring of species,
the monitoring of management indicators,

144
00:10:20,330 --> 00:10:25,970
the monitoring of the general context, the
monitoring of global impacts;

145
00:10:25,970 --> 00:10:30,120
all of this implies
a strong and efficient coordination and sometimes

146
00:10:30,120 --> 00:10:34,300
a prioritization,
due to means and resources not always being

147
00:10:34,300 --> 00:10:35,300
available.

148
00:10:35,300 --> 00:10:40,240
Finally, note in summary the need to build
up on the monitoring.

149
00:10:40,240 --> 00:10:44,490
It's not enough to have all the data,
you need to also analyze and communicate these

150
00:10:44,490 --> 00:10:47,050
results
to all the parties involved.

151
00:10:47,050 --> 00:10:53,380
You should not hesitate to use graphic tools,
charts, visual tools to render this information.

152
00:10:53,380 --> 00:10:59,780
That's it, this sequence is completed, have
a nice day!

